    plus a smaller router/specialist model; keep cloud LLMs as a fallback via a unified gateway
    (LiteLLM). Sources: https://huggingface.co/Qwen/Qwen2.5-72B-Instruct , https://huggingface.co/
    meta-llama/Llama-3.3-70B-Instruct , https://github.com/BerriAI/litellm
  - Memory and retrieval should default to Postgres + pgvector (existing), with a path to Qdrant/
    Milvus for scale; add reranking for quality. Sources: https://github.com/pgvector/pgvector ,
    https://qdrant.tech/documentation/ , https://github.com/milvus-io/milvus , https://huggingface.co/
    BAAI/bge-reranker-large
  - Observability should be local‑first: OpenTelemetry + Langfuse or Phoenix, optionally LangSmith for
    tracing only. Sources: https://opentelemetry.io/docs/ , https://github.com/langfuse/langfuse ,
    https://github.com/Arize-ai/phoenix , https://docs.smith.langchain.com/
  - Primary risks are tool‑call reliability, long‑running workflow durability, and secret management;
    mitigation is strict schema enforcement, queue‑based execution, and formal RBAC + audit logging.
    Sources: https://modelcontextprotocol.io/ , https://github.com/guardrails-ai/guardrails , https://
    developer.hashicorp.com/vault/docs

  Detailed Layer Analysis

  Layer 1 — Local Model Selection & Inference

  - State of the Art + Recommendation: Use vLLM as the primary inference server and benchmark
    Qwen2.5‑32B/72B and Llama‑3.3‑70B quantized (AWQ/GGUF) on RTX 5090; add DeepSeek‑V3 and Mixtral
    8x22B as benchmarks for MoE tradeoffs. Sources: https://docs.vllm.ai/en/latest/ , https://
    huggingface.co/Qwen/Qwen2.5-32B-Instruct , https://huggingface.co/Qwen/Qwen2.5-72B-Instruct ,
    https://huggingface.co/meta-llama/Llama-3.3-70B-Instruct , https://huggingface.co/deepseek-ai/
    DeepSeek-V3 , https://huggingface.co/mistralai/Mixtral-8x22B-Instruct-v0.1
  - Alternatives & Tradeoffs: TensorRT‑LLM for maximum throughput/latency (higher setup cost),
    llama.cpp for CPU/GPU hybrid and GGUF portability, Ollama for developer convenience. Sources:
    https://github.com/NVIDIA/TensorRT-LLM , https://github.com/ggerganov/llama.cpp , https://
    github.com/ollama/ollama
  - Implementation Notes: Run 2‑model setup: a “fast router” (7B–14B) and a “reasoning model” (32B–
    72B); implement a model router that falls back to cloud for complex tasks. Source (router/
    gateway): https://github.com/BerriAI/litellm
  - Success Criteria & Benchmarks: Target <2s median latency for typical responses, ≥8k context, and
    stable throughput under concurrent sessions; measure tokens/sec and p95 latency for each model/
    quant. Use standardized prompts and workloads.
  - Risks & Mitigations: 70B quantized may still be slow; mitigate by using 32B as default and gating
    70B to complex tasks; keep CPU offload as a contingency (llama.cpp).
  - Sources: https://huggingface.co/Qwen/Qwen2.5-72B-Instruct , https://huggingface.co/meta-llama/
    Llama-3.3-70B-Instruct , https://huggingface.co/deepseek-ai/DeepSeek-V3 , https://docs.vllm.ai/en/
    latest/

  Layer 2 — Agent Architecture & Orchestration

  - State of the Art + Recommendation: Use LangGraph for stateful, resumable agent flows with explicit
    nodes for triage, analysis, planning, drafting, and approval gates. Sources: https://github.com/
    langchain-ai/langgraph
  - Alternatives & Tradeoffs: AutoGen and CrewAI are good for multi‑agent simulations but less
    deterministic for durable workflows; DSPy is strong for programmatic prompt optimization but not a
    full orchestration system. Sources: https://github.com/microsoft/autogen , https://github.com/
    crewAIInc/crewAI , https://github.com/stanfordnlp/dspy
  - Implementation Notes: Persist state in Postgres (deal‑scoped) with explicit “checkpoint”
    transitions; each node emits structured outputs and logs decisions to an audit table.
  - Success Criteria & Benchmarks: Zero lost work after restart; sub‑second router decisions; full
    audit trail with replay support.
  - Risks & Mitigations: Graph complexity can increase debugging cost; mitigate by enforcing node
    contracts and keeping a small number of stable workflow types.
  - Sources: https://github.com/langchain-ai/langgraph , https://github.com/microsoft/autogen

  Layer 3 — Tool Integration & Execution

  - State of the Art + Recommendation: Keep MCP for interoperability and expose critical operations as
    internal function tools with strict schemas and validation (JSON schema + guardrails). Sources:
    https://modelcontextprotocol.io/ , https://github.com/guardrails-ai/guardrails , https://
    github.com/dottxt-ai/outlines
  - Alternatives & Tradeoffs: Direct function calling offers lower latency and stronger typing; MCP
    offers interoperability and external tool access.
  - Implementation Notes: Build a “tool registry” with read/write separation and approval gating; run
    write tools via a queue that requires human approval when required.
  - Success Criteria & Benchmarks: ≥99% tool call success rate; no hallucinated parameters; 100% of
    write actions logged with approvals.
  - Risks & Mitigations: Tool schema drift; mitigate with contract tests and CI validation for every
    tool signature.
  - Sources: https://modelcontextprotocol.io/ , https://github.com/guardrails-ai/guardrails , https://
    github.com/dottxt-ai/outlines

  Layer 4 — Memory Architecture

  - State of the Art + Recommendation: Keep Postgres as system‑of‑record; use pgvector for embeddings
    by default and add reranking for quality (bge‑m3 + bge‑reranker). Sources: https://github.com/
    pgvector/pgvector , https://huggingface.co/BAAI/bge-m3 , https://huggingface.co/BAAI/bge-reranker-
    large
  - Alternatives & Tradeoffs: Qdrant/Milvus/Weaviate for higher‑scale vector search and hybrid
    indexing; Chroma is simpler but less scalable. Sources: https://qdrant.tech/documentation/ ,
    https://github.com/milvus-io/milvus , https://github.com/weaviate/weaviate , https://
    docs.trychroma.com/
  - Implementation Notes: Separate memory layers: working memory (session state), episodic memory
    (deal events), semantic memory (vectors), and artifact memory (documents in dataroom).
  - Success Criteria & Benchmarks: RAG precision@k and recall@k above baseline; retrieval <250ms p95
    for common queries; zero cross‑deal leakage.
  - Risks & Mitigations: Vector quality drift; mitigate by periodic re‑indexing and embedding model
    versioning.
  - Sources: https://github.com/pgvector/pgvector , https://qdrant.tech/documentation/ , https://
    huggingface.co/BAAI/bge-reranker-large

  Layer 5 — Hybrid Cloud Integration

  - State of the Art + Recommendation: Use a unified LLM gateway with routing policies that prefer
    local models and call cloud only for high‑complexity tasks. Source: https://github.com/BerriAI/
    litellm
  - Alternatives & Tradeoffs: Direct cloud SDK calls are simpler but make cost tracking and routing
    harder; a gateway adds complexity but enables centralized governance.
  - Implementation Notes: Define routing rules by task type, confidence score, and criticality; log
    every cloud invocation with cost metadata.
  - Success Criteria & Benchmarks: ≥80% local task completion; cloud usage only for complex/ambiguous
    tasks; graceful fallback if cloud unavailable.
  - Risks & Mitigations: Over‑routing to cloud increases cost; mitigate with periodic review and
    policy tuning.
  - Sources: https://github.com/BerriAI/litellm

  Layer 6 — Observability & Debugging

  - State of the Art + Recommendation: OpenTelemetry for traces/metrics/logs, Langfuse or Phoenix for
    LLM‑specific observability, optional LangSmith for tracing only. Sources: https://
    opentelemetry.io/docs/ , https://github.com/langfuse/langfuse , https://github.com/Arize-ai/
    phoenix , https://docs.smith.langchain.com/
  - Alternatives & Tradeoffs: LangSmith is best‑in‑class but hosted; Langfuse/Phoenix provide local
    control and can integrate with OTel.
  - Implementation Notes: Standardize event schema for tool calls, decisions, costs, and outcomes;
    build a “decision replay” view.
  - Success Criteria & Benchmarks: 100% trace coverage for tool calls; replayable runs; median trace
    ingestion <5s.
  - Risks & Mitigations: High telemetry volume; mitigate with sampling policies and per‑deal trace
    retention windows.
  - Sources: https://opentelemetry.io/docs/ , https://github.com/langfuse/langfuse , https://
    github.com/Arize-ai/phoenix

  Layer 7 — Reliability & Production Readiness

  - State of the Art + Recommendation: Use a queue‑based task system (Redis + Dramatiq/Celery) for
    durable steps and retries; write each state transition to Postgres. Sources: https://redis.io/
    docs/latest/ , https://dramatiq.io/ , https://docs.celeryq.dev/en/stable/
  - Alternatives & Tradeoffs: RabbitMQ provides strong delivery semantics but adds operational
    overhead; Redis is simpler and sufficient for a local deployment. Source: https://github.com/
    rabbitmq/rabbitmq-server
  - Implementation Notes: Add idempotency keys, outbox pattern for external writes, and explicit
    recovery procedures for partially completed workflows.
  - Success Criteria & Benchmarks: No lost work on restart; recoverable state for every deal; retry
    success rate >95% without duplication.
  - Risks & Mitigations: Duplicate actions or stuck jobs; mitigate with idempotency and dead‑letter
    queues.
  - Sources: https://dramatiq.io/ , https://docs.celeryq.dev/en/stable/ , https://redis.io/docs/
    latest/

  Layer 8 — Security & Access Control

  - State of the Art + Recommendation: Protect all externally exposed endpoints with Cloudflare Access
    (Zero Trust), enforce RBAC/ABAC in the API, and store secrets in a dedicated secrets manager.
    Sources: https://developers.cloudflare.com/cloudflare-one/ , https://developers.cloudflare.com/
    cloudflare-one/connections/connect-networks/ , https://developer.hashicorp.com/vault/docs
  - Alternatives & Tradeoffs: Casbin (lightweight RBAC) vs OPA (policy‑as‑code); choose based on
    complexity and team size. Sources: https://github.com/casbin/casbin , https://github.com/open-
    policy-agent/opa
  - Implementation Notes: Separate read/write scopes, require approvals for write tools, and ensure
    all sensitive operations are auditable.
  - Success Criteria & Benchmarks: Zero secrets in repo; full audit trail for approvals; verified
    access control for each role.
  - Risks & Mitigations: Misconfigured access policy; mitigate with policy tests and least‑privilege
    defaults.
  - Sources: https://developers.cloudflare.com/cloudflare-one/ , https://developer.hashicorp.com/
    vault/docs , https://github.com/casbin/casbin

