1. Executive Summary
We are building the industry's first "Local-Sovereign" Deal Lifecycle Management System.
ZakOps is a high-stakes operational platform where AI agents manage financial deals, analyze CIMs
(Confidential Information Memorandums), and orchestrate pipeline transitions. Unlike commercial SaaS
agents that are brittle, opaque, and privacy-leaking, ZakOps is durable, deterministic, and fully
observable, running entirely on local high-performance hardware (RTX 5090).
The Core Decision: We reject the "black box" agent hosting model (LangSmith Agent Builder) in favor of
 a Local-First, Graph-Based Architecture.
The Winning Architecture:
*  Intelligence: A hybrid brain dominated by local 32B-parameter models (Qwen 2.5/3) running on vLLM
for sub-second tool use, escalating to cloud SOTA (Claude/GPT-4) only for complex strategic reasoning
[A][B].
*  Orchestration: LangGraph serves as the state machine, replacing fragile procedural code with a
graph of persistent nodes. This guarantees that if the system crashes, the agent resumes exactly where
 it left off (Time Travel/Replay) [A][B][C].
*  Data & Memory: We consolidate "Brain" (Vectors) and "State" (Checkpoints) into a unified PostgreSQL
 backbone. This reduces infrastructure sprawl and ensures transactional integrity for deal data
[A][C].
*  Tools: A hardened Hybrid Tool Gateway that wraps the existing MCP (Model Context Protocol) server
with strict Pydantic validation and human-approval gates for high-stakes actions [A][B].
Why This Wins: It leverages the unique advantage of the RTX 5090 (32GB VRAM) to run "GPT-4 class"
tool-using models locally, eliminating latency and privacy risks while maintaining the auditability
required for financial operations.
